	<tr>
		<td colspan="2"><hr class="sep" /><div class="quotetitle"><b>Quote:</b></div><div class="quotecontent">at least the example you posted, looks too much like monochrome.<br /></div>
<br />I guess the secret to making good graphics is to draw them as monochrome, and then add color afterwards. If you turn an image to monochrome, you'll likely reconize it. If you preserve colors but make all the same lightning level, you will most likely not reconize anything. The proof is here : <a href="http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/HSL_and_HSV" class="postlink">http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/HSL_and_HSV</a> Look at the image in the middle of the article, when they removed the 'L' componant, nothing is reconizable.
<br />
<br />Oh and the stauration is always on maximum on the NES because of the palette itself, so it doesn't even enter into consideration.
<br />
<br />That said, after drawing a monochrome image, you'd still want it to look good colored, and that's why you should use tricks like Celius said.
<br />
<br />BTW I belive there is already a Gameboy version of SF2 which features low resulution and monochrome fighters. Also it does everything with background so that the sprites could get 4 colors + transparent, which isn't possible with sprites. Obviously the graphics were originally drawn for the SNES and scaled down for the Gameboy.

		

		</td>
	</tr>
	</table>


